Creating a basic weather projection app using OpenWeatherMap's API involves HTML for structure, CSS for styling, and JavaScript for fetching and displaying the weather data. You'll need an API key from OpenWeatherMap to access their data. Let's get started!

### Step 1: Get an OpenWeatherMap API Key

1. Go to https://openweathermap.org/api and sign up.
2. Find the API key in your account settings or the email they send upon registration.

### Step 2: Create the HTML File

Create a file named `index.html` and add the following code:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Weather App</title>
    <link rel="stylesheet" href="style.css">
</head>
<body>
    <div id="weather-app">
        <div class="search">
            <input type="text" placeholder="Search for a city..." id="search-box">
            <button id="search-btn">Search</button>
        </div>
        <div id="weather-display">
            <!-- Weather data will go here -->
        </div>
    </div>
    <script src="script.js"></script>
</body>
</html>
```

### Step 3: Add CSS for Basic Styling

Create a file named `style.css` and add the following styles:

```css
body, html {
    margin: 0;
    padding: 0;
    font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
}

#weather-app {
    width: 80%;
    max-width: 600px;
    margin: 20px auto;
    text-align: center;
}

.search input, .search button {
    padding: 10px;
}

.search input {
    width: 70%;
    margin-right: -4px; /* Removes the gap between input and button */
}

.search button {
    width: 30%;
    cursor: pointer;
    background-color: #007BFF;
    color: white;
    border: none;
}

#weather-display {
    margin-top: 20px;
}
```

### Step 4: JavaScript to Fetch and Display Weather Data

Create a file named `script.js` and add the following code:

```js
const apiKey = "YOUR_API_KEY_HERE"; // Replace it with your API key
const searchBtn = document.getElementById('search-btn');
const searchBox = document.getElementById('search-box');

searchBtn.addEventListener('click', function() {
    const cityName = searchBox.value;
    const apiUrl = `https://api.openweathermap.org/data/2.5/weather?q=${cityName}&appid=${apiKey}&units=metric`;

    fetch(apiUrl)
        .then(response => response.json())
        .then(data => {
            displayWeather(data);
        })
        .catch(error => console.error('Error fetching data:', error));
});

function displayWeather(weather) {
    const weatherDisplay = document.getElementById('weather-display');
    if (weather.cod === "404") {
        weatherDisplay.innerHTML = '<p>City not found. Please try again.</p>';
    } else {
        weatherDisplay.innerHTML = `
            <h2>${weather.name}, ${weather.sys.country}</h2>
            <p>Temperature: ${weather.main.temp}°C</p>
            <p>Weather: ${weather.weather[0].main}</p>
            <p>Humidity: ${weather.main.humidity}%</p>
        `;
    }
}
```

### Step 5: Test Your App

- Make sure your API key is correctly inserted in the `script.js`.
- Open `index.html` in your browser.
- Enter a city name and click "Search" to display the weather.

### Additional Enhancements
- Implement error handling for failed API requests.
- Add more features, such as a 5-day forecast or adding icons to represent the weather conditions.
- Improve the app's styling to make it more visually appealing.

